If we choose to write optional<User*>, then we have three possibilities. The point is that we don&#x27;t have to do that in C++, we can write optional<User> and be certain that the returned value is either empty or a User.<p>Compare this with a function that returns a string:<p><pre><code>    string get_name();
</code></pre>
In C++, the caller of this function knows that a string is always returned. Null isn&#x27;t part of the picture. The string object itself holds a pointer to some heap data, but that&#x27;s not something the user has to deal with.<p>PS: I&#x27;ve done my fair share of programming in Haskell so I know the advantages it has :-)
